{{About|the ballpark in Brooklyn|the Major League ballpark in St. Louis of the same name|Union Grounds (St. Louis)}} {{wide image|Union grounds 1865.jpg|600px|Union Grounds in 1865|45%|right|alt=Union Grounds in 1865}} '''Union Grounds''' was a [[baseball park]] located in the [[Williamsburg, Brooklyn|Williamsburg]] section of [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]]. The grounds opened in [[1862 in sports|1862]], its inaugural match being played on May 15.{{cite news|title=Inauguartion of the Union Base Ball and Cricket Grounds--Grand Opening Game--2,000 to 3,000 Spectators present.|url=http://eagle.brooklynpubliclibrary.org/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Archive&Source=Page&Skin=BEagle&BaseHref=BEG/1862/05/16&PageLabelPrint=&EntityId=Ar00203&ViewMode=GIF&GZ=T|accessdate=15 July 2012|newspaper=Brooklyn Eagle|date=16 May 1862}} It was the first baseball park enclosed entirely by a fence, thereby allowing proprietor [[William Cammeyer]] or his tenant to charge admission. This permitted paying customers to watch the games from benches in a stand while non-paying spectators could only watch from embankments outside the grounds.{{cite news|title=Great Base Ball Match. Second Contest for the Champion Silver Ball.|url=http://eagle.brooklynpubliclibrary.org/Default/Scripting/ArticleWin.asp?From=Search&Key=BEG/1862/07/22/2/Ar00201.xml&CollName=BEG_APA3_1861-1864&DOCID=80630&PageLabelPrint=&Skin=BEagle&AppName=2&GZ=T&sScopeID=UDR1&sPublication=BEG&sSorting=IssueDateID%2casc&sQuery=%22Union%20Ball%20Grounds%22&rEntityType=&ViewMode=GIF&GZ=T|accessdate=15 July 2012|newspaper=Brooklyn Eagle|date=22 July 1862}} ==Overview== The ball grounds was built on a large block bounded by Harrison Avenue, Rutledge Street, Lynch Street, and Marcy Avenue. A writer for the Brooklyn Eagle described the field in 1862:
"The buildings occupied last winter are left standing, used pretty much for the same purposes as them.[sic] Near these a long wooden shed has been erected, capable of accommodating several hundred persons, and benches provided for the convenience of the fair sex... Several acres more have been added to the enclosure, which is fenced in with a board fence six or seven feet in height. On the southeast corner a large and commodious club house has been erected, containing accommodations for three clubs. The field is now almost a perfect level, covering at least some six acres of ground, all of which is well drained, rolled, and in a few weeks will be in splendid condition... Several flagstaffs have been put up, from which floated the banners of the clubs o'er shadowed by the nations' ensign."
During its early years Union Grounds was the home field for several ballclubs, notably including the [[Eckford of Brooklyn|Eckford Club]], 1862 and 1863 champions of the [[National Association of Base Ball Players]]. In 1868, the [[New York Mutuals|Mutual Club of New York]] moved in from [[Elysian Fields, Hoboken, New Jersey]], long-time home of [[Manhattan]] clubs but never enclosed. The ballpark's entrance was on Rutledge Street, and a one-story building in right field, 350 feet away from home plate, was in play. After formation of the first professional league, the [[National Association of Professional Base Ball Players|National Association of ''Professional'' Base Ball Players]], Union Grounds was home to the [[New York Mutuals|Mutual Club]] from [[1871 in sports|1871]] to [[1876 in sports|1876]] (the only year as a member of the new [[National League]]), [[Eckford of Brooklyn]] of the National Association in [[1872 in sports|1872]], and the [[Brooklyn Atlantics|Atlantic Club of Brooklyn]] of the National Association from [[1873 in sports|1873]] to [[1875 in sports|1875]]. It also served as home field for the "[[Hartford Dark Blues|Hartford of Brooklyn]]" team during the [[1877 in sports|1877]] [[National League]] season. On July 26, 1878, the final major league game was played on the grounds, with Providence defeating Milwaukee 4-1.[http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1878/PKL_NYC011878.htm Retrosheet.org] The grounds continued to host barnstorming major league clubs, amateur clubs and independent clubs through the 1882 season.[http://www.covehurst.net/ddyte/brooklyn/union.html BrooklynBallParks.com] The park did not sit idle during the winter. Its field was flooded and served as the rink for an ice skating club.{{cite news |title=Death List of a Day |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1898/09/07/archives/col-andrew-sheehan-dead.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 7, 1898 |accessdate=2011-08-20}} An unusual feature of the park was the presence of a pagoda in center field. [[File:Marcy Avenue Armory jeh.jpg|thumb|right|240px|The Marcy Avenue Armory now occupies the southern half of the site of the Union Grounds.]] Union Grounds was demolished in July of [[1883 in sports|1883]].{{cite news |title=Base-Ball; The Metropolitans Defeat the Baltimores After A Close Game |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1883/05/20/archives/baseball-the-metropolitans-defeat-the-baltimores-after-a-close-game.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 20, 1883 |accessdate=2011-08-20}} Heyward Street now runs through the site, and as of 2009 the Juan Morel Campos Secondary School stands to the north of Heyward Street and the Marcy Avenue Armory stands to the south of it, with no historical marker or any other indication of the land's significance to the history of baseball. == Sources == *''Green Cathedrals'', by Philip J. Lowry, 1986. *''Ballparks of North America'', by Michael Benson, 1989. Name: Union Grounds *''Long Before the Dodgers'', by James L. Terry, 2002 ==References== {{Reflist}} ==External links== * [http://www.covehurst.net/ddyte/brooklyn/union.html BrooklynBallParks.com] {{NewYorksportsvenues}} {{coord|40|42|14|N|73|57|10|W|display=title}} [[Category:Defunct baseball venues in the United States]] [[Category:Sports venues in Brooklyn]] [[Category:Baseball venues in New York City]] [[Category:Former sports venues in New York City]] [[Category:Demolished sports venues in New York (state)]] [[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in New York City]] [[Category:1862 establishments in New York (state)]] [[Category:Sports venues completed in 1862]] [[Category:1883 disestablishments in New York (state)]] [[Category:Sports venues demolished in 1883]]

{{Infobox Americas Cup Yacht | title = Valkyrie II | image = Cutter Valkyrie II-01.jpg | caption = ''Valkyrie II'' during the 1893 cup races. | club = {{yachtclub|Royal Yacht Squadron}} | nat = {{flag|United Kingdom|civil}} | ac_year = 1893 | type = | class = | designer = [[George Lennox Watson]] | builder = [[D&W Henderson]], [[Partick]] | launched = April 29, 1893 | owner = [[Windham Wyndham-Quin, 4th Earl of Dunraven and Mount-Earl|Lord Dunraven]] | skip = | crew = | wins = | boats = | fate = Sank July 5, 1894 in the [[Firth of Clyde]] | displacement = 140 tons | length = {{convert|35.84|m|abbr=on}} (LOA)
{{convert|26.06|m|abbr=on}} (LWL) | beam = {{convert|6.80|m|abbr=on}} | draft = {{convert|5.03|m|abbr=on}} | sail = | notes = }} {{coord|55.614|-4.950|display=title|region:GB_scale:50000}} '''''Valkyrie II''''', officially named ''Valkyrie'',{{refn|Although officially named ''Valkyrie'', [[Official number|ON]] 102581, the "''II''" was used to differentiate Lord Dunraven's three yachts of the same name{{cite book|title=Mercantile Navy List|date=1894|publisher=Spottiswoode|location=London}}|group= n}} was a British racing yacht that was the unsuccessful challenger of the [[1893 America's Cup]] race against American defender [[Vigilant (yacht)|''Vigilant'']]. ==Design== ''Valkyrie II'' was a [[gaff-rigged]] [[Cutter (ship)|cutter]]. She was designed by [[George Lennox Watson]] and built alongside ''[[HMY Britannia (Royal Cutter Yacht)|HMY ''Britannia'']]'' at the [[D&W Henderson]] shipyard, Meadowside, [[Partick]] on the River Clyde, Scotland in 1893 for owner [[Windham Wyndham-Quin, 4th Earl of Dunraven and Mount-Earl|Lord Dunraven]] of the [[Royal Yacht Squadron]].{{cite book|last=Latham|first=George|entry=Valkyrie II|title=A Dictionary of Names, Nicknames and Surnames, of Persons, Places and Things|year=1904|publisher=George Routledge & Sons Press|pages=318|chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/dictionaryofname00lathuoft#page/318/mode/2up}} ''Valkyrie II'' had a steel frame, a wooden hull, and a pine deck.{{cite web|title=Ready for a great contest: Both Valkyrie and Vigilant in Fine Racing Trim|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1893/10/05/109730601.pdf |format=pdf |publisher=New York Times|accessdate=30 July 2012}} ==Career== ''Valkyrie II'' was launched on April 29, 1893, a week after ''Britannia'', and sailed to the U.S. that October to compete in the eighth America's Cup where she faced ''Vigilant'' in a best three out of five races format sailed on alternating courses. The races were sailed October 7, 9, and 13, 1893 off [[Sandy Hook, NJ]] just south of New York. The first and third races were 15 miles to windward off Scotland Lightship and return to leeward, the second race was a 30-mile equilateral triangle. {{cite web |title=Vigilant |url=http://32nd.americascup.com/en/acclopaedia/circlinggalaxy/bateau.php?idContent=4692 |work=32nd America's Cup |accessdate=30 January 2012 }}{{dead link|date=December 2014}} {{cite news |title=Vigilant Wins! |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=450&dat=18931014&id=CJdGAAAAIBAJ&sjid=VS4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4559,7312613 |accessdate=2012-04-22 |newspaper=The Quebec Saturday Budget |date=Oct 14, 1893 }} In the first race on October 7, ''Valkyrie II'' won the 11:25 am start by 15 seconds and one boat length. At the first mark, ''Vigilant'' held a nine-minute lead. ''Vigilant'' crossed the finish line 7 minutes ahead of ''Valkyrie II''{{mdash}}8 minutes 48 seconds in corrected time. In the second race on October 9, ''Vigilant'' won the 11:25 am start by 5 seconds, but ''Valkyrie II'' worked out to an early lead of 5 boat lengths in a building {{convert|24|mph|km/h kn}} breeze. By the first mark, ''Vigilant'' held a five-minute lead and worked out to a 9-minute lead at the second mark. At the finish ''Vigilant'' beat ''Valkyrie II'' by 12 minutes 30 seconds{{mdash}}10 minutes 35 seconds in corrected time. In the third race on October 13, 1893, he ''Valkyrie II'' led the windward leg, but lost a spinnaker at the two-thirds point of the downwind run. At the finish, ''Vigilant'' beat ''Valkyrie II'' by 40 seconds in corrected time to successfully defend the cup. The World reported it as the fastest race ever sailed, over a course of 15 miles to windward and return under reefed sail and a gale.{{cite web |title=This Week in Herreshoff History |url=http://herreshoff.org/news/herreshoff_history.html |publisher=Herreshoff Marine Museum |accessdate=2012-04-22 }} ''Valkyrie II'' existed for barely a single year. On July 5, 1894 this Cup contender was struck amidships by A. D. Clarke’s cutter yacht ''Satanita'' at the start of the Mud Hook Regatta on the [[Firth of Clyde]]. Lord Dunraven and all his crew and guests were rescued, though one crewman was severely injured and subsequently died. ''Valkyrie II'' broke up and sank nine minutes later. {{cite news |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1894/07/06/106911287.pdf |title=The Yacht Valkyrie sunk |date=6 July 1894 |format=pdf |accessdate=2012-04-22 }}{{cite news|title=The Valkyrie Sunk|work=The Times|issue=34309|date=6 July 1894|location=London|page=10}}{{cite news|title=Yachting|work=The Times|issue=34311|date=9 July 1894|location=London|page=7}} ==Notes== {{Reflist | group=n}} ==References== {{reflist}} ==External links== *{{cite web |url=http://www.glwatson.com/ |title=G. L. Watson, ''Valkyrie II''{{'}}s Designer }} *{{Cite web |url = http://32nd.americascup.com/en/acclopaedia/circlinggalaxy/bateau.php?idContent=4640 |title = America's Cup's AC-clopaedia: ''Valkyrie II'' }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} *{{cite web |url=http://jsjohnston.org/~valkyrie_iii.html |last=Johnston |first=John S |authorlink=John S.
